comment: Eiko Strader is the gem of the WGSS department: her teaching style incentivizes reading (which is a reasonable amount, interesting content), she has incredible lectures, and you learn so much from her! Gives amazing feedback, is very encouraging; this class changed my life!
Very inconsiderate and wastes a lot of papers. Inattentive and unprofessional.

Professor Taylor's class was reasonably good. It consisted of a good amount of reading each week with a discussion board post, plus students were assigned to do presentations on the readings for each lecture. There were a few short papers in between and a take-home final. Overall, a reasonable course if you don't stress yourself out with the work.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: Professor Hernandez-Fujigaki is a great guy. Though the syllabus shows a LOT of reading, you really only have to do the readings for the one week that you present during the semester. The rest you can take from other students' presentations, if you want. The midterm and final are take-home and he grades the research paper leniently. Recommended.

10% attendance/participation, 20% weekly quizzes, 30% research paper, 40% final exam. Class is lecture-based with some discussion interspersed. Quizzes are annoying but fair provided you read the papers. Papers are often cryptic and jargon-y, but explained in class. Little guidance on research paper, but accessible during office hours.

Warshaw is a decent professor - encourages class discussion and likes to hear student opinions. Class is based on a lot of current events and data which is interesting, but sometimes its unclear what you should be note-taking on, and the powerpoint isn't posted online. Weekly quizzes based on readings but straightforward if you do the reading
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: The course is by no means difficult if you pay attention. LT. Lazott makes class interesting by inserting personal anecdotes, and inviting guest lecturers. I would recommend the class, and LT. Lazott. A word of wisdom, turn things in on time, or early. He gets a lot of emails, and sometimes his inbox is full. He will take off points for late work.

you will be spending $400-$600 for this class, including a film camera if you don't have one, 2 100 sheet box of papers which each is $100 ( you will run out ), and also films. The class was so much fun, but it requires lots of work outside of the class so don't take it if you have a busy schedule. She came every Friday to help us with the prints!

Margaret is a very sweet, chill teacher. I took this just to get a GE out of the way. It requires a lot of out of class time doing prints, but if you get over how much time it takes, it's actually pretty enjoyable. Margaret is an amazing teacher and I'm glad I took her class. But be warned, you do have to buy all (and I mean ALL) of the materials.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Skip class? You won't pass.--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: Dr. Erica Brown is an amazing professor! Her lectures are really interesting and she knows an insane amount about Judaism. Class is reading-intensive and she is a tough grader (she expects a lot out of her students). She is super nice and caring and accessible outside of class. Absolutely would recommend.

Dr. Brown is fantastic! She is so nice and she gives fantastic feedback on essays. There's a decent amount of reading, but it's usually not too bad. The course is fascinating, and she's brilliant. She's very accessible, she gets to know her students and really cares. Her lectures often take the form of very interesting class discussions. Take it!!
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Amazing lectures

comment: He's exams are extremely difficul, he doesnt care about his students and will fail you without any consideration. during lecture, he is so boring and despite the material being extreemly difficcut he does not make it any easier to understand it, also you are graded by very few things (2 midterms + final) and if you do bad one of his exams, drop out
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Tough grader

comment: Fast-paced class, and covers virtually every single subject in the textbook, he does a good job considering that. Homework is assigned every class. Exams are typically medium difficulty homework problems, but lots of people ended up doing bad. Advice : make this class a priority, study hard for exams and practice HW & lecture problems.
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Lecture heavy

comment: He assigns homework every lecture but doesn't upload the homework assignments online so you have to be in class every morning to know what the homework will be on. You also have to turn in homework at the beginning of every lecture. He checks attendance every time and wastes the first 15mins of class every single lecture.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--BEWARE OF POP QUIZZES--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: This class was horrible. The material is difficult and Critchfield doesn't do an adequate job of explaining concepts. Definitely read the textbook and use as many online resources as you can, he doesn't make this course easy. Final is worth 45% of your grade, doesn't provide you w/ equation sheet beforehand, expects you to memorize everything.

Very awful at teaching. Tries to teach Matlab-doesn't allow you to work in class on your laptop. no codes are done in class and everything is taught through her notes on Microsoft word. very confusing.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Tough grader

comment: Dr. Papadopoulos is extremely knowledgeable. The homework/programming examples are basically taken straight from her lectures. It's really important to ask questions, especially when debugging programs. She gives real-life examples that build on top of one another. Fun fact - she created the algorithms used in FitBit. Top 3 professors here.
She is terrible, doesn't help the students , the exams are so hard and they made no sense.

Shes a terrible professor, I'm confident she has no clue how to actually program, let alone teach it. Your final is writing a giant program with pen and paper. This is a C programming class how is writing a program with pen and paper and no computer program or code guide actually reasonable. Shes also not clear on her grading procedure whatsoever.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: Class is very fast paced and dense with difficult material. She assigns 7 programming examples during the semester that can take upwards of 8 hours to do correctly. The midterm and final are absurdly difficult. She doesn't tell you how much she curves and teaches the material by reading off a word doc. Class was the hardest one i have taken at GW.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--Tests are tough

comment: Prof. Eich is really going to push you, which might no be what you are looking for in an art credit, but he is very talented and thoughtful and you will learn a lot, and probably become a better photographer in the process. If he sees you are improving and working hard throughout the semester you will do well. Highly recommend taking his class.

he's got a good energy to his teaching. very thorough explanation and reasonable expectations. Though not necessary, she sends an email recapping each class, which is oddly appreciated and nice. He's on top of his stuff and is overall a good teacher.

Prof. Montroso is great at teaching. I never once felt asleep in the class due to his interactive lecture. Because he is young, he likes to spin Medival literature with Millenial trending topics as well as letting you being creative with your work. He is also very accessible outside class so definitely reach out to him if you need help.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Hilarious

comment: I really enjoyed taking professor Montroso's class. At first I wasn't excited to learn about Medieval literature, but he made the subject matter so interesting! He is very knowledgable and passionate about his students. Grading is very fair, just a few close reading assignments, midterm paper, and final project/paper. An awesome WID class!

Missed the midterm for a family emergency, wasn't allowed to retake it. Did all extra credit & showed up for most every class, lab, group project & still got a D. Unreasonable amount of work, no tolerance for students who lack passion or understanding of astronomy, though its a required course. Long boring lectures with many tangents. AVOID

Prof. Young is well knowledgeable about the political economy of the Middle East. Her lecture is kind of boring. You will be required to lead a discussion in one of the classes, write a long (5000-7000 word) paper, write an op-ed and participate.

Professor Young really knows what she is talking about and is very knowledgeable in the field. Lectures are engaging, but it is very difficult to take notes off of the slides. It is only graded by a few things, and you need to put a lot of effort into studying the material, but overall a good class if you are interested in Middle East.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Respected--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: Absolutely incredible professor. Paper, Midterm and Final are your only grades but if you actually pay attention in class and read the textbook (which is free) you'll be fine. It's not a very reading heavy class and the readings she does give you are actually very interesting and easy to understand. A boss woman that deserves a lot of respect.

While an incredible woman with a very well respected career she is a terrible professor. She will make you work hard for an A. One paper, midterm, and a final. Midterm and final are 20 short answer questions where she wants very specific and detailed answers. Her lectures are pointless and you end up having to teach yourself all the material.

Amazing class and professor. If you are genuinely interested in the material during the lecture you don't even need to do the readings to get an A. She's got a great sense of humor and cares about her students, she also brings in amazing guest speakers. Only drawback is mandatory attendance but that just means you'll do better in the end.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria--Hilarious

comment: He's a very knowledgeable guy, and it's very obvious he's passionate about philosophy and loves to talk about it. He is a slightly harsh grader in the beginning, but you get better at writing the later assignments or exams with his feedback. All in all, a cool class to take for the Local and Civic Engagement requirement.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--GROUP PROJECTS

comment: Lots of readings, but you don't necessarily have to do them if you are already knowledgeable about the topic. She grades heavily on participation and writes down people's names every time they talk. The final class grade is made up of three short (800-900 words) papers and the participation grade.

She's a lawyer, not a professor. She's nice. She cares. She's just not good. Graded on 3 short papers and participation. She jumps around and seems to have no experience in pedagogy. She gives out As, but she expects everyone in the 40 person class to participate. Half the time you're listening to classmates instead of learning.

One of the best professor's at GW! Professor Negroponte is an expert in the field of Latin America Studies. Having never taken a course in this area before, she made it a breeze. She will make you work for a good grade. However, she is extremely approachable and friendly and encourages student's to come and talk to her outside of class.

Amazing lecturer. If you skip class, you wont do well; but you dont want to miss lectures anyways because theyre so good. Theres one huge group paper, 5 online quizzes, and 1 online final. ALL HARD but graded easy. Quizzes arent worded well if written by the TAs. But you can email her to argue your case and get points back.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures--GROUP PROJECTS

comment: He's a really endearing man, a little too happy-go-lucky sometimes, but it works for me. Assignments are pretty easy and straightforward and his mentors are always there to help you. Would recommend as it's a great GPA booster.
stand up guy, very understanding and easy going. gives of high school teacher vibes though other than that he is a great professor..

Great professor to take for BADM1001. Most of your grade comes from attendance and participation and then the case study project. Other assignments are easy and I did most of them right before class began. The biggest part is showing up and the rest will come easily. Mr. O'Connell is a great teacher and really cares about how his students do.

Professor Pechnikova is amazing! She genuinely cares about her students and how they do. She also always hands back everything that was graded the very next day. All feedback she gives is helpful, and she would add stories about Russian culture since she lived and grew up in St. Petersburg. I took her for 3 semesters and learned so much.

Anna Dmitrievna is my favorite professor at GW so far. She is so personable and funny, and she truly cares about the success of her students. She is to-the-point in her teaching style, and you should be prepared to meet her expectations, but that doesn't mean she won't help you through any difficulties as long as you let her know beforehand.

My only complaint is that we often strayed from the syllabus. Pechnikova is a bit quiet but she gives students the opportunity to come to her office hours for extra practice which was very helpful. Also gave us study guides for all of the exams (including the final) as well as the final OPI.

The class is hard no matter who you take (as the class itself is standardized within the dept) and thats coming from a native speaker. However, she is so willing to help anyone who needs it and made many additional practice sessions outside of her office hours. She is super nice in general and flexible if one is absent on a graded assignment day.

Great micro teacher. The exams are very much like the hw. There is a curve given if you regularly attend class. Textbook is useful, but I didn't use it after the first two weeks or so (after consumer optimization). definitely take advantage of him reading your drafts if you can (get started early on papers!). very friendly and accessible.

This has been one of my favorite econ classes so far  Ani explains concepts clearly and has weekly problems sets that the exam is modeled after. If you have any questions he is accessible outside of class and gives great advice on the homework, econ careers, and best donuts in DC. Take him if you get the chance!
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Caring

comment: best micro theory teacher at gw. he's a world bank economist so he brings real world exp. to the classroom. class is writing heavy (3 papers) but u can show him drafts --not hard. exams are modeled off the optional hw problems. beyond being a teacher, silwal is definitely someone an aspiring economist should want to know. also runs marathons! good!

Professor Guru was very thorough and made sure that all of the questions from students were answered. He is an expert and has profound knowledge in computer architecture. I would definitely recommend his class.
During the lectures, he keeps us engaged by guessing the reason while predicting the evolving architectural enhancements happened in each topic. Course is project heavy instead of homework.

Super chill, approachable, and understanding guy. What he teaches you is realistic and applicable - especially the intro to RFPs and practice pitch. Attendance partially based on daily quizzes. Look over the slides/assigned chapter before tests and you'll be fine, no tricks or miscommunication whatsoever.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Clear grading criteria--GROUP PROJECTS

comment: take him!!!!

Prof Patrongic is really sweet and caring. I was scared of taking Bio, but she was really clear. Midterm and final aren't the end all be all, and she gives you a study guide. There are a ton of grades so I think it's pretty tough to get a bad grade. She learns all of the students and is accessible outside of class. Take this if you need a science.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--Clear grading criteria

comment: Pretty interesting class overall but there's a weird mix of subjects which are overly specific and very basic, like studying the anatomy of a neuron at the same time as defining "natural selection"
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Group projects--Lecture heavy

comment: One of my favorite professors ever. She is so nice and thorough. her lectures are well organized and easy to understand. Not to mention she is such a gentle and sweet person, it is hard to not respect her.
She really tries. Read the textbook and prepare for quizzes. No midterm or final.

The class itself isn't too hard, but I did not enjoy this professor. She did not how to control or grab the attention of the lecture hall. She was constantly annoyed at us. I thought I signed up for Professor Scully. You have to attend 70% of the lectures to get full participation. There are pointless in class group activities that count a lot.

Professor Patrnogic is awesome. I was nervous about taking a science class but it ended up being one of the classes I looked forward to most. She gives lots of quizzes and in class activities that aren't complex. No midterm or final which was great. There is little to no homework outside of class, and if you study for the unit tests you'll do fine.

With the class size of 200+ students that have to take this as a requirement I think she is doing a great job and does all she can to make the material easier. Ppts are always clear and easy to follow, and if you take notes, and stay on top of things you will do well. She is always willing to help with anything.

Outside of class, she's great. In class, different. She's never taught a large lecture class before and the way the large class is set up is different from any other class you'll ever take. The final is cumulative and there isn't much direction on what to study for. Lecture slides don't have much info on it and she says most of the information.

As a non science major, I was wary going into this class. However, because of Prof Patrnogic I look forward to this class. In microbes, the quizzes aren't impossible, but don't expect to get A's on all of them. Also, they do not count too much for your grade- an A is manageable even with iffy quiz grades. She is so kind and funny. HIGHLY recommend.
Jelena is absolutely amazing! She's so sweet! Just make sure you read the textbook she puts up on blackboard - you'll need it for the quizzes!!

Prof. Patrnogic is great. Always willing to help and answer all the questions. If you follow the lectures and take notes you will do well in class. It is not an easy A, you have to work for it, but it is feasible and she will help you until the very end. She gives extra credit opportunities too.
ratingTags: ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--Caring

comment: Great professor. Willing to help and answer all the questions. Lectures were ok. Exams were not always easy but if you follow the lectures and take notes you will do ok.

As a non science major this was not an easy course. However the professor made it easier by implementing both lectures and different activities to bring the subject of genetics closer, and show the bigger picture. If you take notes and follow the lectures, you will be fine. She is always available outside class and ranswers all the questions.

As a business major who hates science, this class was difficult. It was a class meant for non science majors and I think she sometimes would forget that, even though she did try to tone down the content. Definitely need to review notes between classes to do well. If you play the game and study, you will do fine; otherwise, you will fail.
Great professor. Very nice and laid back. Lectures were a little dry at times. Fair grader. Gives extra credit opportunities.
ratingTags: Clear grading criteria--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: Definitely one of the easier instructors in the department. In Intro Microbio, the lecture component had 3 non-cumulative 45-50 question multiple choice exams (with some short answer and true/false questions). She gives you an hour to complete the exam and all of the questions come from the lecture slides. Use the textbook to complement the PPTs.
ratingTags: TEST HEAVY--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: Clear slides.

She would read off of the slides in lecture and try to explain but she went too fast and wasn't good at it. I had to go back into the textbook to reteach myself some things, but if you ask for help or explanations individually, she does a much better job and is very kind. Extra credit ops in class, weekly graded hw assignments, 2 midterms, 1 final
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: The class is hard, but it's stats. But she definitely tries to help when you ask for it. I didn't go to class much so I missed out on the extra credits, but I've attended her office hours a few times to ask for help and extensions and she's pretty flexible and understanding.
ratingTags: LOTS OF HOMEWORK--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: I thought she was pretty accessible when asked for help. Her slides are pretty helpful for understanding some of the material because she uses a lot of examples. The class started really fast so it was hard to follow at first, but then again it's stats.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: "if you don't do well its really entirely your fault" "I have a full-time job, I don't know what you want me to do"

She is literally reading her useless slides every class. She is extremely irresponsible that when students ask about reviewing materials, she said, "this is only my part-time job, don't ask me too many questions". Do not take her course even when you run out of options.

Class is essentially meaningless because she just reads the slides and if you ask a question she often questions back why you don't get it if she just said it. If you read the textbook this class is very manageable though. Allows you to have "cheat sheets" in every test with equations.
Terrible professor. She reads off the slides like I did in 5th grade and mocks students for asking questions. Don't go to class, read the book.
Her lecture is hard to understand and the slides are not helpful. Don't take her course unless you don't have other options.

One of the worst instructors ever. Weve done 5 cases that had good structure to learn from, but she does not provide any solid material with lectures and wastes time on cases each week and presentations (each session, a team present in front of the class for at least an hour). Shes also ill organized and all over the place.

Her Advanced Financial class is taught entirely on cases (with one "assessment" in the middle of the semester) and the rest is participation. There's a case every two weeks, with a three page max write up for each while your group will also do a presentation for one of them. If you're confused, you can meet with her and she'll talk you through them

Harriston is an awesome guy, he has awesome stories and is very engaging. The guest speakers are amazing and you really learn a lot. The problem is that I didn't have much experience in Journalistic writing and therefore I found it very stressful that everything was a grade, nothing was a 100 if you did it. I get why, I just I found it stressful.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Skip class? You won't pass.--So many papers

comment: Professor Harriston is a truly amazing professor. His classes are very discussion based, and he has amazing insights and stories.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria

comment: One of my favorite professors at GW by far. Lots of experience at WaPo, uses his connections to bring in interesting guest lecturers. Great with feedback and replying to his emails. Just follow his guidelines (which are industry standard) and pay attention and you'll do fine. Genuinely enjoyed going to his class, gives easy quizzes.

Keith was one of the best professors I have ever had the privilege of learning from. He made class entertaining and interesting while still always teaching us the fundamentals of journalism. His assignments were fun and he had super interesting guest lecturers come in from various media outlets. He knows his stuff, curses a lot, and is a real gem.

Professor Harriston is a good professor that is knowledgeable about writing articles. The class does have a paper assignment almost every week. However, Professor Harriston is available to meet with you to discuss edits. It is important to show up to class because there is typically a quiz at the beginning.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.--SO MANY PAPERS

comment: Definitely not a very engaged professor. Will grade your work harshly but provide little feedback and the feedback he does provide is not at all helpful. Is not good at responding to email which makes communicating with him very difficult.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.--SO MANY PAPERS

comment: I am so glad I was part of this thesis seminar run by Professor Sheline. I am really proud of the thesis I wrote, which is thanks to how responsive she was and the in-depth feedback she was willing to offer. She pushes her students because she cares and she believes you can achieve a lot if you put the work into it. Great professor and mentor.

Professor Sheline was one of the most considerate professors I've ever had. She really cared about students and the fact that we had other assignments, something other professors rarely acknowledge. Each time we turned in an assignment over email, she provided thorough feedback on what we needed to change to improve our final paper.

Prof. Sheline is a wonderful professor - she goes above and beyond to make herself accessible to students. She provides timely and meaningful feedback. Her course was extremely challenging but we learned SO MUCH and actually came out of the class with a solid writing sample.
She is very understanding, truly cares and pays attention. Lots of work but helps you organize yourself to be successful.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: The class was challenging and a lot of work- there is no doubt about it. However, Prof Sheline's openness to let you choose your research gives you the chance to put a lot of work into something u care about. she is just a caring person who constantly helped work with me even when constant illness kept me away or unable- a gem who actually cared

Professor Sheline is probably the coolest professor I've had so far at GW. She is young enough to understand student challenges and university lifestyle, but she is also super successful (already) and it is a privilege to take her class. She helped me write the longest paper I've ever written, and somehow made it one of the easiest assignments.

Professor Sheline is a saint. She teaches complex concepts and somehow makes it so simple and easy to understand. It's actually kind of astounding that some people failyou would have to explicitly try to not get a good grade. She will also let you veer off assignments to make your work useful for the future (grad writing, job samples, etc..)

Professor Sheline easily stands out as one of the best professors I've had at GWU. Her directions were extremely straightforward, as well as her grading criteria. She made complex concepts easy to understand, & gave students every opportunity to succeed. Some students freaked out before we ever had an assignment, don't listen to the naysayers.

Professor Sheline is a wonderful professor. Yes, the class is relatively demanding in terms of workload; however, she is extremely responsive to student questions, and is more than willing to work alongside students to tailor course expectations to their own situations. She cares more about learning outcomes than grades, which is refreshing.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Caring

comment: Professor Sheline's research methods class teaches you how to write a research paper. It is not easy, but it is not supposed to be. She provides ample feedback at every stage of the research process to ensure that her students grow both as researchers and writers. She genuinely cares about her students and offers ample extra credit opportunities.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--Caring

comment: Prof Sheline is kind and understanding and easy to talk to. However, this class was/is overwhelmingly stressful and MUCH more work than it needed to be (30 page paper and endless readings). Prof Sheline also missed a lot of class, for acceptable reasons, but students suffered nonetheless. If you need to take IA Research Methods, look elsewhere.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--SO MANY PAPERS

comment: Professor Sheline is probably one of the most considerate professors I've had at GWU. She gives solid feedback on assignments and truly cares about her students. comment: Contrary to the prior review, I had a great experience with Prof. Sheline in Research Methods. She was one of my favorite professors this semester and I genuinely felt like she cared about her students. Would recommend!

comment: Meant as a class intended to teach how to conduct research, she throws you with minimal guidance into independent research. comment: Prof. Gerrad Taylor is the funniest teacher I have had! This class is so much fun and you do many acting activities which eventually prepare you for the final scene presentation. Highly recommend
Boring voice, just lectures and doenst move. Hes not an interactive teacher so you need to focus on the lecture or study at home and hes a stick for attendance
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--SO MANY PAPERS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: I have to agree with the negative ratings. It was really annoying how often, and last minute he would change his mind. I studied very hard for his cumulative final just to find that he changed his mind 1 day before the exam. He doesn't realize that as students we need organized teachers, and just does he wants (without care about his students)

Thank god this semester he taught a special topics course, so he is not permanently a teacher here. He alone could get enough bad ratings to get GW in trouble as a school. I really think he's not fit for a job with students. Before teaching us, someone needs to teach him to better his egotistical attitude and mean personality.

His class was just exhausting and hes really annoying. He gives a 40% midterm, and a 50% final because he doesn't want to do more work than that. Does bare minimum to be employed. He doesnt feel for students, and really deosnt care at all to help anyone. Only take if you can memorize 20 chapters+ and can put up with a really arrogant, bad teacher.

Really really mean & horrible. He only cares about his outside job. Meaning he does the bare minimum for the course-basically assigns the whole book and tells u to memorize EVERYTHING (20 chapters in my case). U won't get any help from him, when u ask for help he will refer you to the book. He is unapologetic, and mean. Shouldn't be teaching. BAD.

Professor lives & breathes bank regulation. Showed "The Big Short" movie for extra credit. Invited senior exec from FDIC to talk about course topics. Sends out expectations via clear announcements. Does on-demand office hrs at Gelman Starbucks. Tests are similar to the concepts from the end-of-chapter questions. 75% of class got an A or a B.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Hilarious--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: If you havent taken intermediate micro or macro or are non-econ then you will struggle bc material is dense. Otherwise class is an easy A. Know the textbook inside out.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: He is really knowledgeable but does not know how to transmit the information to students. He also expects from students to be able to answer exam questions, but does not go over them in class. Be ready to teach yourself and solve hw questions that you haven't seen before.
He is ok but if you can take the other professor than you should. Other professor that teaches this is much easier, much friendlier and explains concepts much better.

Hands down the worse professor that I have had during my time at GWU. He is so full of him self to the point that it is difficult to listen even during lecture. He makes me feel incredible uncomfortable and is incredible rude. He pretends to care about students but he really does not care about them. Take the other prof that teaches this class.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--TEST HEAVY--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: When I didn't get an A on a test (which asked questions totally unrelated to the study guide), he accused me of not taking my degree seriously even though I had met with him outside of class several times, had all A's on my homework and participated in every single class. A professor should want you to succeed, not berate you after a test.

I'm not sure how much of the coursework was dictated to him and how much was his decision. I was really interested in taking his class because he has a great background and a wealth of knowledge. None of that came through in class. Go get The World Is Flat on audible. There, you're done. This class ultimately led to me dropping the program.

Be prepared to read and memorize a lot. The examinations are very detailed and you will need to know the material from the textbook in order to pass any of his examinations. You should also focus on other research that is applicable to the field since you will be required to write two papers for grading. Overall, he is a reasonable professor.
He is not teaching, he is reading book! You should learn it yourself.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Caring

comment: A good professor - an instructor who explains new concepts in a clear and succinct way - can help you learn a subject quickly and provide you with the building blocks necessary for further study. But if your professor appears to be incompetent -- for example, failing to explain information clearly and your academic performance suffers.

She is not very understanding of anything but she is a fair test (not quiz) giver. Reading the textbook thoroughly and taking good notes is a must, if you're spending less than 3hrs on a chapter you won't pass the quizzes - I think there were 5 and she dropped lowest. 2 midterms, 1 final, cheat sheet for all (very fair). READ READ READ
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: Professor LeBlanc does not lecture. You will have to rely entirely on the book and in class problems to pass this course. She will never fully explain a concept or particular problem and most of the time will just tell you to figure it out. All I have to say is thank goodness for the curve.

comment: Chill dude. He is very critical of your first papers, but it only helps you to become a better writer in the end. ratingTags: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Graded by few things

comment: Pros: Easygoing, flexible due dates, willing to meet outside of class for one-on-one help, interesting as a person, cares about students. Cons: Vague criteria, unhelpful instructions, unnecessary homework. Often seems to have no idea what he is talking about. I don't think I actually learned anything about writing during this course.
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Accessible outside class--Participation matters

comment: Professor Miller was a good teacher. He was a little bit harder just because he really would only go along with your topic if he agreed with the argument and he would make comments that are questionably condescending, but I really needed to learn how to write and he taught me so much about how to think about writing an essay and I can finally write
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Lots of homework--Clear grading criteria

comment: I wanted to like this class but couldn't. Overall, Prof. Miller seems passionate about what he teaches and can be pretty laid back. Prof. Miller is super chill and always willing to work with students on their papers (and offers extra credit). comment: Professor Miller is best described as a self-identifying hipster. His insights about music are interesting and the class is enjoyable if you are into music. ratingTags: Lots of homework--Graded by few things--Tough grader

comment: Professor Miller is super chill, kind, and generous. However, I was frustrated because his steps for writing papers don't seem illogical, and are tedious and structured. ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Lots of homework--Tough grader

comment: Miller was the best university professor I have ever had. This is what you should expect from Miller: he reminds me of The Dude. Miller has high expectations (less about citing and grammar, more the idea/argument). He will always look over your papers before the due date. Lots of student interaction
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: Peter is great. Its more of a life lesson class than a marketing class. Lots of Ted Talks and life advice lectures. Interesting content, little to do with marketing. A good father figure for those missing home. Super-connected in DC community. Knows a guy who knows a guy where youre applying. Loves helping students land jobs. Lets you eat in clas
Prof. Pin was fantastic! Great guy and easy class. He's super helpful and wants everyone to do well. Quizzes are not that difficult, just read the textbook and you'll be fine.

Prof Pin was probably my favorite professor this semester. He is charismatic AF and truly cares about his students. His grading is super fair and he tries to make the class as interesting and relatable as possible. I recommend him !!

Professor Herer is the kindest professor at GWU, she just wants her students to succeed. If you do all the papers you will probably get an A. ratingTags: ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--Caring

comment: A very nice professor with a kind heart. She is very passionate about what she teaches and will give you the opportunity to be flexible for your papers. Really easy grader so getting an A should not be hard.

Professor Herer is the best Professor Ive ever had at this school. She really cares about her students and wants you to succeed in her class! Is very passionate about the class subject material and is very helpful when you go to her for advice and gives you many sources for papers! Wish she taught every class i took.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--Caring

comment: Prof. Herer is great! She is super nice and helpful with writing advice. 3 essays: 5 page, 7 page, then 10-12 page. comment: An amazing professor! He kept class super interesting and really cared for each of his students. He is super responsive outside of class and gives amazing feedback on each paper. comment: Prof. Wang is a very knowledgeable professional in her field, has worked at the world bank, etc... comment: Prof. Wang is a kind women who has earned a fair amount of respect in her field. That being said, she does NOT operate well in a classroom setting. comment: His class is one of the worst I have taken at my three years at GW. Not only is his grading clearly flawed, but his rationale behind it is completely ambiguous. ratingTags: Graded by few things--Test heavy--Tough grader

comment: He is open to listening to you but it is sometimes hard to communicate with him. He uses the book a lot and his lectures do not add much to it despite being mandatory. ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Group projects--Tough grader

ratingTags: Graded by few things--Group projects--Tough grader

comment: He usually teaches grad courses, so an intro class was new for Dr. Lu. Two big group projects; your group remains the same for the semester and is chosen by the professor. Follow his format and you're good.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--GROUP PROJECTS

comment: This class was boring. Never listened to a lecture but attendance was mandatory and there were participation questions throughout the lecture. Just memorized the questions from Tophat that was going to be on the exam before and did alright on the three exams. There were also a couple group projects that were annoying but relatively easy.

4 presentations (1 is with a group) and a final exam. He basically gives you the answers for the final, which is worth the same as one presentation. He is the hardest grader I've had at GW, by far. So nit picky about presentations - if you don't do it exactly his way, you won't do well, period. Unnecessarily stressful, would not take again.

He was actually pretty open minded deep down and willing to give constructive feedback. Also, do work on the group projects...I really enjoyed them.

Lu isn't a bad guy, but he has no idea what he's talking about. His attempts to foster "meaningful debate" on "controversial cultural issues" just came across as ignorant and pretty offensive. The main grade is group projects, and there's no clear rubric of what he wants. The best word to describe this class is "Problematic"

Definitely one of the best professors I've had at GW! He cares so much about his students and their understanding of the readings. Super passionate and knowledgeable about Russian Literature. Class is fairly standard for an intro course. Tries his hardest to be interesting and inclusive. Actually takes into account student feedback. Tests are difficult, but not impossible. You won't regret taking the class.
Professor Bonnah is so nice and passionate about Arabic! He is knowledgeable and a genuine man. I thoroughly enjoyed his class and hope to take him again in the future.

Bonnah is the best! He genuinely cares about everyone. Just show up to class, and you'll be fine.
One of the best professors at GW. He is very nice, and he cares about his students.

I love Bonnah!!! This is my second time having him! He's such a sweetheart who's completely understanding. He makes everything so simple. There's literally no reason for anyone not to get an A. Just talk to him if you have any trouble!!
He's super kind and funny, doesn't give a lot of homework and believes most of the learning is through practice which we do during class. He gives study guides and is a really fair grader.

Professor Bonnah is my favorite Arabic Professor to date. Every day, he showed up to class with an infinite amount of enthusiasm for not just the language, but for teaching that language to others as well.
She's a really nice teacher and has really great insight, as she worked for the state department.

She's a very clear professor who wants her students to do well. You learn a lot, she isn't the easiest grader but she's really nice and always willing to meet with students to help their grade. comment: Professor Yun is the best professor I've ever had! She is so kind and gives great feedback on your drafts. comment: I completely loved this course. She was very compassionate and you can tell this is her passion. comment: I totally totally loved Professor Yun's Fiction Writing class. She is a really sweet, funny, chill professor who definitely cares about making you the best writer you can be. comment: Really straightforward class just study what he tells you to study and you should be fine. Lectures are a bit dry but he gives good feedback and is really clear about what he wants. This guy is the man. Easiest A at GW and ever in my entire life. Im not sure what the other ratings are for but this dude actually gave out As

comment: Given the other professors for the course, Holliday is a solid choice. His lectures are a bit dry (although he occasionally slips in a great offhand joke) but the class is straightforward. comment: Professor Eastwood was an excellent professor this semester. Overall, a great person and teacher and would take another class of his if I had the opportunity.

comment: I started this class not being very interested in conflict resolution but I learned so much and found the class very interesting. You have to participate a lot so do the readings.

comment: My favorite professor at GW so far. He's really caring and wants all his students to succeed. Didn't think I would like accounting but actually really enjoyed his class and I'm looking forward to taking intermediate accounting with him.

Always great to have a professor like this guy who is knowledgeable in his field and genuinely wants his students to do well. Professor Moon is a terrific guy and great professor who is always upbeat and enthusiastic about teaching a class in which the material is normally anything but exciting. Would take again.

Joon Moon is one of the first professors I've seen at GW who genuinely cares about his students and makes a point to know each one of them. comment: Extremely nice and caring professor. I would say this was the best class I have taken due to the easy course combined with the awesomeness of Professor Pertner, or EB as she has us call her. I recommend to anybody.

Really really really easy PSC 1001 class. You'll learn a good deal, you don't need the textbook, and if you pay attention in lecture you'll do fine on the exams. No paper either, which is a huge plus.

I did not think that Intro to Philosophy would be such a difficult class. I was expecting to learn more about the overall history of philosophy and its different schools, but instead we had to form our own opinions. Good for critical thinking, though. Great professor.

comment: Sam is a really great TA who helps you understand the material better. Hes also really funny and looks exactly like Ed Sheeran which is a bonus

He was fun to chat with in office hours and was able to help me out with declaring an anthropology minor.

Sam's a great assistant and wants students to be able to learn the material. He's pretty critical with feedback and can go off on rants and tangents but is very constructive, clear in his grading, and got coffee for students that got A's on both exams, so that's a bonus.

comment: Densford's a good grader and her assignments are helpful. Heavy reading, but enjoyable.

comment: Prof. Yu is probably an amazing piano instructor, but she isn't right for teaching a seminar class. Assignment instructions were vague and confusing. comment: If I could take every SMPA class with Leiby, I would. This man really made it worth it to go to an 8 AM class. comment: Prof Niznik was knowledgeable in his field, and his tests were straightforward. Small workload, and he'll give you a good grade on the mini-essays if you answer the prompt. He's quiet, his lectures are boring, and he may be scarred from working at Starbucks, frothing milk for 7 years. He doesn't make the class hard, and he doesn't want you to fail.

Professor Niznik is super caring and nice, and even though he mainly reads off his slides, you don't need to buy the book, and it ends up being a pretty easy class. His exams are extremely straightforward, as he gives a study guide that lists every single topic that will be on the exam.

Super nice guy, really cares about his students. He totally understands what it's like to be a college student and will cut you some slack if needed. He presents the information in a very clear way and makes a strong effort to engage everyone in discussion. Wish more professors were like him! The people who don't rate him 5 stars DIDN'T TRY AT ALL

He really cares about his students and if you show up to class and take notes you do not ever have to read the textbook. Exams are straightforward and he gives study guides for everything. Easy class, nice professor - can be a bit boring but the tradeoff is not having a lot of work to do outside.

Prof. Niznik really does care for students but reads directly off the slides during lectures which I dont like. pretty boring professor but easy class if you take good notes and do the readings

comment: A genuinely inspiring professor who is not only fun and interesting, but wants you to succeed. Ultimately, a fun class with a great professor who loves what he does. Highly recommend!
ratingTags: Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.--Inspirational

comment: Prof. Baker is incredibly condescending. He's not very understanding of those who are not well versed in theatre and is unreasonable with his expectations therein. He knows his stuff, but doesn't convey it well. I tried to get interested in theatre, but his unreasonable expectations and condescending attitude made being motivated here difficult.
not that helpful to your writing skills, easy to follow but hard to earn the grade, lots of time required.

He's the best professor I ever had in GWU! He's caring and soooo kind! He will give you specific feedbacks on your paper and really patient to every single words of in both class and office hour! He's also really humorous to make his 'boring' literature class fun! Take him! You can even become friends! He's also not a tough grader!

He is friendly and humorous. The course is content-rich, yet easy to follow. We had many fun exercises and he gave many inspirational speeches. I learned many useful principles of writing with him. I strongly recommend him for English as Second Language students.

Dr. Paiz's EAP class was challenging, but he found a way to make it funny whenever he could. Sometime his joke were not that funny, but at least he tried. Anytime I want to meet during office hour he tries to be available. I always feel better once I meet him.
He's tough, but cares about students. Makes a required class a little less painful. Sometimes distracted onto tangent during lecture.

Dr. Dumouchel was really a caring professor, who wanted each of her students to succeed. LOVE LOVE LOVE this professor! She now works at Indiana University Bloomington, just for the record. Super cool class, very nice teacher, awesome.

comment: If you do not take this class to fill one of your science credits, you are doing it wrong. Laurence is amazing! She's very knowledgeable about the material and makes it easy to understand. Exams are easy and the labs are manageable.

comment: Dumouchel is a great professor. She clearly knows a lot about anthropology, but is still able to explain concepts well to those who don't. She also cracks some funny jokes in lecture. Attendance is mandatory though, as she asks super easy clicker questions each class.

comment: Professor Dumouchel gives great lectures and always makes them humorous and relatable. She also lets lecture out upwards of 15 min early every class. comment: Professor Dumouchel is so sweet and genuinely cares about her students and the subject. Her exams were hard to study for (a lot of material) but only multiple choice. good

comment: Professor Haynes is very disorganized and does not explain her criteria for grading. Do not be fooled by the past positive reviews. Lectures are confusing and she is very discouraging. Avoid and take class with Professor Longoni.

comment: Prof Haynes is hilarious. I look forward to going to class! Her quizzes/tests are very fair and she is always willing to help you out. She makes the class fun especially for an intro to italian course! Must take!

Quizzes are where the points are at: VERY detailed/minutiae laden. The big ppts & paper are dissected, but great learning tools. Her feedback is crucial. Some things will be outside your expertise & you'll just lose points. Just address her points & ask her questions! Look at as many model papers as you can for reference, esp. in class journals.

Beware! Main professor vs. Alec: Make clear with Alec what format he wants for the papers because if you follow the syllabus instructions you will lose points. There's some disagreement there. Alec is laid back & has great real world experience. Before each class he gives you golden summaries of the lectures, spit that back in the exam essays.

This is a tough class. The homework assignments are where the big points are. The quizzes are specific and you win some you lose some, but the feedback on homework is crucial. In class participation is where you have a chance to clarify things you don't understand. Take advantage of this because the grading is tough and detailed. Good luck!
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: This class is not only hard, but the professor thinks that you are a genius in stats. If you can go with another professor, do it.
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Tough grader

comment: Only reads from power points. Very boring class. You're better off reading the textbook. He thinks everyone automactically understand stats. Its a hard class.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: Prof Gallelli Huezo (AGH) is the sweetest, most caring professor I have had at Georgetown. She absolutely loves the subject matter she teaches (and is also super impressive that she was a practicing architect before this and has since switched into academia), but is even more passionate about her students. Love her - makes anything interesting TAKE

Prof. Gallelli Huezo is by far one of my favorite professors at GWU. She makes lectures incredibly interesting and you can see how passionate she is about the subject, which makes the learning experience all the better. She is an incredibly knowledgable and sweet person that truly wants to help you learn. A real gem.

This class was amazing! Professor Huezo is super well-informed, kind, and engaging. You'll never want to miss her lectures! She also makes the most beautiful powerpoints (is this a weird thing to say?), so don't miss out!

This professor is legit the most understanding and caring I have had while at GW. She will make you feel honored to be her student. I had one of the roughest semesters in my whole time at GWU and she really helped me out every step of the way. Dont miss class though, she knows everyone by name bc she cares that much.

She is an amazing professor! She truly cares about all her students and is easily accessible outside of class. She has a few quizzes, a short paper, and midterm and final. She does review sessions, which are super helpful. She is not super strict on reading, but make sure you go to class because notes are based on her lecture. Take the class!!!!

Amazing professor, very kind and caring of all her students. Learns everyones names the first day of class. Her lectures are incredible, she knows what she is talking about and you can tell she loves it. I would take every single class she teaches. Her tests are not difficult at all she is not there to trick you she just want you to learn.

I'm pretty sure Fall 2018 was Dr. Grinberg's first time teaching IA Research Methods. She's an absolute gem and really tries to make a dry subject interesting. She 100% knows that IA kids don't always want to do math/quantitative research so she doesn't force you to. She's out here trying to make this class as engaging as possible. A+ meme content
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: Pretty sure this was Nellis' first time teaching at GW and it shows. She's one of those people that definitely knows the content, but struggles to teach it in an accessible way. The class is structured oddly & covers a lot of seemingly irrelevant material. Midterm exam was difficult and also just poorly written. Hard to do well in this class.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: She gave me an 89.7, I was the only fluent Spanish speaker in the class...

comment: She is the first person I ever met who actively doubted my 'initiative' in any course I have taken. Dieppa-Perea makes students uncomfortable when asking for clarification on specific exam questions. Her grading criteria are highly subjective and inconsistent, similar to the entire Spanish dept. Escalate issues to dept. level for better treatment.

comment: The class was engaging and given that it was small, there was always room for discussion. She'd also explain topics that I didn't understand when I'd reach out. Overall, I enjoyed the class, I received an 89.7 (which I thought was harsh) but I did find her to be a great professor

I loved having her as a professor. You have to participate in every single class because discussion is a big part of the grade, but if she sees that you're putting in the effort you'll be okay. She also gives extra credit opportunities for every test.

comment: Prof. Dieppa Perea is really great, which is important when the course itself is so excessively/terribly regulated by the department. She seems truly invested in how her students do & taking her class, while challenging, has helped me a lot & really revived my interest in the language. Expect lots of work, but about as good as a prof can make it.

As much as I dislike the department here, Michelle makes the class a little less painful. Typical structure of span classes, w/ confusing grading and lots of assignments- but she really works with us to make it accessible. Expects only Spanish in class and grades pretty hard, but challenges students to grow and enjoy the language.

The course, titled "Protest & Resistance in Contemporary American Lit" covered a really interesting array of novels. The course was discussion based and required a weekly discussion post. Prof. Moser is very approachable and gives great feedback as well.

Exams  difficult bc youre very pressed for time (many people didnt answer some questions bc of this). Must go to class to understand topics and how HE defines things/explains them. Labs are very easy and essentially grade boosters. Homework is difficult bc of his definitions are slightly confusing/ seems like he tries to trick you
Do your assigned reading and attend class. Many papers on philosophy.

comment: He's a really interesting professor with lots of insight and experience which he very candidly shares with the class. comment: Hes an engaging teacher with great stories about working for the Treasury. Gudur is a funny and smart lawyer, and he teaches as such, so expect to participate a lot. There are four textbooks. His tests are hard but he tells you all of the questions ahead of time. comment: Assignments and material were easy, especially if you've taken International Politics/International Affairs. Exams are on general concepts and the answers are clear. comment: Gudur is not a horrible guy, seems intimidating, but actually not a mean person. Only two exams, two group presentations, and participation for your grade. comment: Professor Bayard is really such a nice guy. He runs his class as more of a discussion on writing (both short stories by published authors and peoples' work in the class). interesting class, lots of speakers

The students that rated Professor Lewis poorly probably haven't taken a higher level sports analytics class before. He may seem dry but he knows his stuff and if you put in the work, you'll receive a good mark. Would take him again.

I really appreciated Professor Lewis' real world experience. The most awful professor I have ever met. I chose his Sports Analytics, which turned out the be the worst course I have ever take. The worst professor I have ever met! He gave sport analytics lectures in GW, however, he doesn't really teach ANYTHING! Professor Fisher is nice enough, but she can be pretty boring. She does not give great feedback or help even when you visit her office hours, but she will definitely recognize your effort. comment: Very interesting class. She isn't the most engaging speaker but is very passionate about her work and uses relevant examples in class.

Easy A for UW. Do the work and the readings and you will do really well. She cancels class often. The readings are somewhat optional. One of the Easier UW classes to take. No final research paper. comment: Great class. If you put in work and she can tell you are making an effort you are likely to get a good grade. comment: Professor Azar made this course extremely fun. I feel I learned a lot and that the concepts she taught in this course will be very useful in my future. comment: Dr. Prasad is my favorite prof I've had so far. She's incredibly wise about social justice issues and has done some amazing work. Professor Prasad is very sweet and cares about Human Services. She is flexible with students and not a tough grader. Classes are, however, unstructured. One second we're talking about one thing, the next another. She also likes to talk A LOT. Does not allow electronics.

This Professor is extremely unclear and assigns so many assignments that you really don't even know what you are doing in this class. Even if you show up to every class and email her for clarification on topics she is still the most confusing and frustrating person in the world. DO NOT TAKE HER CLASS.

she is literally the worst uw teacher. she makes you got to events in the city that take 4 hours to complete and assigns an insane amount of homework and work that is stupid for uw. the content is beyond boring and has nothing to really do with real life application so please dont take this class

She's a new professor and still has a lot to learn. She had a really skewed understanding of what an appropriate amount of reading was. comment: Connie's very helpful and caring in and outside of the class. She's not a tough grader so if you REALLY do your homework and paper, you'll get a great grade. comment: Really sweet. Wants students to learn and improve. Very understanding and patient, care about all of her students. Would definitively take her again!

One of the Best professors here! She gave me regular feedback and she was always available during her office hours and after class. She would support you if she sees you are serious and trying hard. Don't take her class if you are looking for an easy A..

Awesome knowledgeable teacher! I took Arabic before with other good professors. But, Professor Bellali is very unique in her linguistic and pedagogical skills. She is multilingual and speaks 5 languages! She makes sure that you assimilate the information. She expects you to work hard outside the class in return. She is a tough grader but very fair!
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Lots of homework--Tough grader

comment: She is one of the unique Arabic teachers I've ever had. Her linguistic knowledge is unlimited. She has high expectations from advanced students. If you got to an advanced level with little work and a weak command of the language, she will try to push you really hard to get where you should be. She supports hard working students. She is really GREAT

The professor was disappointing, and was an ineffective teacher. Often times, it was unclear if the class was following the syllabus, so it was hard to stay on top of homework and other assignments. She did not have the ability to convey class material clearly, as she was often times unprepared for class, and seemed uninterested.
Very nice teacher. Wants her students to succeed. She will be annoyed if students are unprepared and interested. If you show up, put in effort, and are engaged, you will get an A.

Unfortunately, students were not provided with a reliable syllabus, outline, clear structure, or rubrics for any of the assignments so the class was consequently very disorganized and frustrating. Overall very vocab-heavy course that was not conducive to advanced language application/skill development.

This guy is amazing. He is an adjunct professor and brings over 30 years of experience to the role. He teaches because he enjoys is, and his 2.5 hour lectures are captivating, enjoyable, and entertaining. Not much work, but you'll learn so much. He is one of the best professors I've had in the real estate concentration and at GW.

I really enjoyed this class. What I appreciate is he is open to learning from students and allowing them to guide the discussion. Even though he has a lot to offer with his own perspective and experience, he ensures that students have a voice. He really listened to midterm feedback and experiments with different styles which keeps things engaging.
Relaxed class. I liked the reading choices, and the assignments are straight forward.

Straightforward professor. Young, so understands and relates to students. Take-home midterm and take-home final. One group presentation on a film. A straightforward map quiz. Participation MATTERS (based on the assigned readings). Relaxed class.

comment: Excellent professor! Professor Phaup truly cares about his students and wants them to be successful! He also made Economics very interesting and enjoyable. I would definitely take a class with him again!

Prof. Huntsman is a really nice, approachable lady who is big on discussion and personal interaction. She is very knowledgeable and is great at getting conversations going about difficult topics. She is a very fair grader and gives wonderful feedback. All in all, would definitely take a class with her again.

Rly not sure how to feel about Maratea. He makes a lot of self-deprecating jokes that are funny, but also make students uncomfortable. The class really isn't that bad, but RJ is a bit intimidating. He is an understanding professor tho.

RJ is great, a real gem of the CJ department. Would definitely take him again. 4 pretty easy tests as long as you study the study guides he gives you. He grades final paper kind of tough, but I still did fine in the class. His lectures are hilarious, he sometimes goes on tangents, but I genuinely enjoyed going to class.

Amazing professor. Goes off on tangents a lot, but he's hilarious and covers all the material he needs to. Gives detailed study guides before exams, and if you know it all it's an easy A. He grades a little harsh on the papers, but gives extra credit throughout the semester. Will definitely take more of his classes
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Hilarious--Amazing lectures

comment: RJ is a fantastic professor. Yeah, he can get off on some tangents and he kept on adjusting the syllabus, but his lectures are informative and entertaining. You can tell he really cares about the material. It also helps to go to his office hours, he was more than happy to clarify what was expected on the assignments.

BEST. PROFESSOR. EVER. RJ made class hilarious every single day, even when some of the content was dull. I really enjoyed RJ's class, he gives a study guide before the exam. He's so hilarious and wants you to do well, come to class take good notes. Also gives extra credit.

comment: The best professor at GW.. do all of the extra credit and you will get an amazing grade. He is an amazing lecturer. I am a B student at GW and ended with close to a perfect average. Final is very fair.
Stay away. The way the professor grades assignments and exams makes it almost impossible to do well.

comment: Lecture's are what most of tests are based on. Very smart guy, but a tough grader. Gives extra credit for random things occasionally, but not too often.

Maratea is the best. So funny, and explains everything super clearly in lectures. He is a very tough grader on papers, so spend a lot of time on them, but there are only two a year, and both are only two pages. comment: Although he says classes are mandatory, he does not take attendance. However, in class is the only place you get information on the subject and he barely uses the textbook. comment: Very intelligent and passionate about what he teaches.

Professor Holden is perfectly fine and you will do perfectly fine in this class so long as you do the assignments. At the same time his lack of energy (which to be fair is in large part because of it being an evening class and the fact of his humor being so dry) makes the class feel rather unimportant.

Professor Holden is relatively new to teaching. He is a nice professor but often doubts his teaching ability and is not prepared. He is accessible by email. He is not a harsh grader as long as you turn in your assignments on time you will do fine in class. Will need the books that are assigned for reading. Midterm and final are take home.

comment: Weekly quizzes on Blackboard (very easy), 1 final exam taken mid semester, 1 group project, 1 press release, and 1 paper. Very doable, she does not want you to fail. A little hard to reach out of class, and her expectations for certain things are a little unclear. Willing to work with the class if there is consensus about due dates.
Challenging class but very good professor. He was always available for extra help and tried to help me get my grade up. Interesting topics, thought-provoking lessons.

This was his first semester at GW. Showed up late a few times, grades extremely tough, a few friends in the class had to drop while I'll be retaking. Sometimes he'd give feedback so I'd change what was on my paper and then he'd tell me my correction was wrong tell me to change back to what I already had wrote. Avoid at all costs.
